  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering, including:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Identifying customer sources of funds\n- Assessing potential money laundering risks\n- Establishing customer risk profiles\n\n4. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Implementing internal control systems\n- Training employees\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n\n5. International regulations\n- Complying with FATF recommendations\n- Following international anti-money laundering standards\n- Cooperating with law enforcement\n\n6. Penalties for non-compliance\n- Significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal charges\n- Loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent criminal financial activities and ensure transparency in financial systems.",
